entry.title: Forecasting the number of Crimes in Vancouver with Prophet
entry.summary: In this post, I demonstrate the use of the Facebook Prophet to forecast the number of crimes in Vancouver.

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Introduction">Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#Introduction">¶</a></h1><p>Following on my series <strong><em>Crime in Vancouver</em></strong>, the next step is to forecast the number of crimes. For this task, I'll be using the <a href="https://facebookincubator.github.io/prophet/" target="_blank">Facebook Prophet</a> package.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="Prophet">Prophet<a class="anchor-link" href="#Prophet">¶</a></h3><p>Prophet is an open source software that was released by Facebook in February 2017. It can be implemented in R or Python.</p>
<p>Facebook calls it <strong>Forecasting at Scale</strong> and by scale, they mean:</p>
<blockquote><p><em>1) a large number of people making forecasts, possibly without training in time series methods; and </em></p>
<p><em>2) a large variety of forecasting problems with potentially idiosyncratic features.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>If you are interested to know more about it, you can read their <a href="https://facebookincubator.github.io/prophet/static/prophet_paper_20170113.pdf" target="_blank">paper</a>. Basically, forecasting is not an easy task. If it was, there would be tons of people making money off it, but how many do you know that can make a real good forecast? Maybe one or two who have a lot of experience? Prophet aims to help analysts make fast and reasonable forecasts without the need of a forecasting expertise. Let's try it!</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h1 id="Importing-the-Data-Analysis,-Visualization-and-Prophet-packages">Importing the Data Analysis, Visualization and Prophet packages<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Data-Analysis,-Visualization-and-Prophet-packages">¶</a></h1><hr />
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">fbprophet</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">Prophet</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Processing-and-Transforming-the-data">Processing and Transforming the data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Processing-and-Transforming-the-data">¶</a></h1><hr />
<h3 id="Importing-the-Crime-data-set">Importing the Crime data set<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Crime-data-set">¶</a></h3><p>The data set was cleaned and transformed in my previous post <a href="crime-vancouver.html">"An Exploratory Data Analysis of Crime in Vancouver from 2003 to 2017"</a>.</p>
<p>If you would like to use the same data, you can download it <a href="https://github.com/wosaku/datasets/raw/master/crimes_clean.zip">here</a>.</p>
<p>Let's import it and make it appropriate for Prophet.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [2]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Reading the csv, grouping by day</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'crimes.csv'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">groupby</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">()[</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_frame</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># The input must be a data frame with two columns 'ds' and 'y' </span>
<span class="c1"># (ds is the date and y is the number of crimes). Let's adjust it.</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">reset_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'ds'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can see that there is an outlier (which we saw in my previous post). Let's keep it for now.</p>
<h1 id="Using-Prophet">Using Prophet<a class="anchor-link" href="#Using-Prophet">¶</a></h1><hr />
<p>One interesting feature of Prophet is that it is <em>"robust to outliers, missing data, and dramatic changes in your time series"</em>.</p>
<p>So let's try 3 different models:</p>
<ul>
<li>Model 1 - plain (without removing outliers).</li>
<li>Model 2 - removing outliers.</li>
<li>Model 3 - including holidays.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="Model-1---Plain">Model 1 - Plain<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-1---Plain">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [4]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Starting by making a copy of the data frame</span>
<span class="n">df_m1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># The only transformation we'll do is a 'log transformation' of y</span>
<span class="n">df_m1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">log</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_m1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">])</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now let's run Prophet!</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [6]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Prophet code are basically these lines</span>
<span class="n">m1_plain</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Prophet</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">m1_plain</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_m1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Let's try a forecast for 365 days</span>
<span class="n">future</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">m1_plain</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">make_future_dataframe</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">periods</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">365</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">m1_plain</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">future</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>With a couple of lines, standard parameters and just a few seconds, Prophet has completed the forecast. Now let's use its plot function.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">m1_plain</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">forecast_m1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This is interesting. Prophet displays the general, weekly and monthly trends.</p>
<ul>
<li>In the first subplot, we can see that the number of crimes decreased until 2011 and then start increasing.</li>
<li>The weekly subplot shows that Friday and Saturday have more crimes.</li>
<li>The yearly subplot shows that summers months have higher number of crimes.</li>
</ul>
<p>Now let's measure the error for this model. For that, I'll be using the <em>Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE)</em>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># First, let's get some useful variables: "y" for the actual value and "n" for the number of observations.</span>
<span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_frame</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">y</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'ds'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">int</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># The forecast is 'log transformed', so we need to 'inverse' it back by using the exp</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m1_exp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">exp</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">forecast_m1</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'yhat'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'yhat_lower'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'yhat_upper'</span><span class="p">]])</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m1_exp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_m1</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'ds'</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Now let's calculate the MAPE for m1</span>
<span class="n">error</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_m1_exp</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'yhat'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">MAPE_m1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">error</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span>
<span class="nb">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">MAPE_m1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[11]:</div>
<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>12.64</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Model-2---Removing-outliers">Model 2 - Removing outliers<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-2---Removing-outliers">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [12]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Make another copy of the data frame as m2</span>
<span class="n">df_m2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">copy</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [13]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Define the Upper Control Limit and Lower Control Limit as 3 standard deviations from the mean</span>
<span class="n">ucl</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">3</span>
<span class="n">lcl</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">3</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Print the number of outliers found</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Above 3 standard deviations: '</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df_m2</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">></span> <span class="n">ucl</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]][</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">count</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="s1">'entries'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">MAPE_m2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">error</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span>
<span class="nb">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">MAPE_m2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>With Model 2 by removing the outliers, the model performed only a little better (0.01%) than the plain model. This is probably because the outliers that were considered were only a few data points (18 of 5295). They were not a sequence of data points that compromised the trend, so in this case, they didn't make much difference. Prophet handled them well in the first plain model.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h2 id="Model-3---Holidays">Model 3 - Holidays<a class="anchor-link" href="#Model-3---Holidays">¶</a></h2><p>Prophet has a nice flexibility of including events (holidays) that impact the trend. To do that, we need to create a data frame with dates (past and future). Another cool thing is that we can add a 'lower' and 'upper' window. For example, if we have Christmas as a holiday and we want to add the Christmas' Eve, all we need to do is to add a 'lower window' of -1.</p>
<p>I'll be using three sets of holidays.</p>
<ul>
<li>One with no added window: Mother's day, Victoria Day, Canada Day, Labour Day, Remembrance Day, Christmas.</li>
<li>Another with a -1 lower and 1 upper window: Halloween, New Year's</li>
<li>And another with a -2 lower and a 1 upper window: BC Day and Thanksgiving (long weekends)</li>
</ul>
<p>Note: in my previous post, there is a heat map showing the average number of crimes per day.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2009-10-12'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2010-10-11'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2011-10-10'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2012-10-08'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2013-10-14'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2014-10-13'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2015-10-12'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2016-10-10'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'2017-10-09'</span><span         <span class="s1">'lower_window'</span> <span class="p">:</span> <span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span>

<span class="c1"># Concatenate all 3 df into 1</span>
<span class="n">holidays_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">concat</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="n">holidays_0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">holidays_1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">holidays_2</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Now we pass the holidays variable when we instantiate Prophet</span>
<span class="n">m3_holidays</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Prophet</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">holidays</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">holidays_list</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">m3_holidays</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df_m1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">future</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">m3_holidays</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">make_future_dataframe</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">periods</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">365</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m3</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">m3_holidays</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">future</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [22]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Inverse the log</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m3_exp</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">exp</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">forecast_m3</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'yhat'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'yhat_lower'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'yhat_upper'</span><span class="p">]])</span>
<span class="n">forecast_m3_exp</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_m3</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'ds'</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [23]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Calculate error</span>
<span class="n">error</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">forecast_m3_exp</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'yhat'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">MAPE_m3</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">error</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">abs</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">n</span> <span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span>
<span class="nb">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">MAPE_m3</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can see that there is a peak every year that model 1 didn't have. This is the result of adding a holiday that had a relevant impact. This is going to be reflected in the forecast.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h2 id="Conclusion">Conclusion<a class="anchor-link" href="#Conclusion">¶</a></h2><p>Finally, to see the forecasted numbers, we can check the forecast data frame:</p>

</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>For example, the forecasted number of crime for 2017-09-01 is 114, with an interval of 93 - 139.</p>
<p><br />
Note about Prophet: it is a very easy tool to use. It is fast, provides a good result and allows for tuning the model. Just a few lines of code and no complex parameters gave us a forecast of the number of crimes.</p>

entry.title: Correlation between Crimes and Google searches
entry.summary: Is there a correlation between the number of crimes in Vancouver and Google searches of crimes? Let's find out!

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Introduction">Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#Introduction">¶</a></h1><p>The goal of this analysis is to check if there is any correlation between google searches of crime and the total number of crimes in Vancouver. The assumption is that the number of searches reflects what's going on in the real world and people's sentiment.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="Google-Trends">Google Trends<a class="anchor-link" href="#Google-Trends">¶</a></h3><p>Google Trends shows how often a search-term is entered relative to the total search-volume. About the data from Google Trends:</p>
<blockquote><p>"Numbers represent search interest relative to the highest point on the chart for the given region and time. A value of 100 is the peak popularity for the term. A value of 50 means that the term is half as popular. Likewise a score of 0 means the term was less than 1% as popular as the peak."</p>
</blockquote>
<p>For this analysis, I'm using the search-term <strong>crime</strong>, for <strong>British Columbia</strong>, period from <strong>2004-01-01 to 2017-06-30</strong>. <a href="https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=2004-01-01%202017-06-30&geo=CA-BC&q=crime" target="_blank">You can check it here.</a></p>
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="The-Crime-data-set">The Crime data set<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Crime-data-set">¶</a></h3><p>The data set is the same I've been using in my series Crime in Vancouver.</p>
<p>It comes from the <a href="http://data.vancouver.ca/datacatalogue/crime-data.htm
" target="_blank">Vancouver Open Data Catalogue</a>.</p>
<p>It was extracted on 2017-07-18 and it contains 530,652 records from 2003-01-01 to 2017-07-13.</p>
<p>The data set was cleaned and transformed in my previous post <a href="crime-vancouver.html">"An Exploratory Data Analysis of Crime in Vancouver from 2003 to 2017"</a></p>
<p><br /></p>
<h1 id="Importing-the-Data-Analysis-and-Visualization-packages">Importing the Data Analysis and Visualization packages<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Data-Analysis-and-Visualization-packages">¶</a></h1><hr />
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Import data manipulation packages</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>

<span class="c1"># Import data visualization packages</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">seaborn</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">sns</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline

<span class="c1"># Ignore warning (Optional)</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">warnings</span>
<span class="n">warnings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">filterwarnings</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'ignore'</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Processing-and-Transforming-the-data">Processing and Transforming the data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Processing-and-Transforming-the-data">¶</a></h1><hr />
<h3 id="Importing-the-Google-Trend-Data">Importing the Google Trend Data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Google-Trend-Data">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [2]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Note: before importing the csv, I cleaned the header and adjusted the date column</span>
<span class="c1"># to include the last day of the month</span>
<span class="n">googletrend</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'googletrend.csv'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Month'</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Taking a look at the first entries</span>
<span class="n">googletrend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[3]:</div>
<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea output_execute_result">
<div>

</tr>

<th></th>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Checking index and data types</span>
<span class="n">googletrend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>We can see that the Google Trend data has 162 entries, which are monthly values from 2004-01 to 2017-06.</li>
<li>The search index column shows the popularity of the search. A value of 100 is the peak of popularity. Other values are relative to the peak.</li>
</ul>
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="Importing-the-Crime-data">Importing the Crime data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Crime-data">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Importing CSV file</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'crimes.csv'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># The crime data starts from 2003, but our Google data starts from 2004. </span>
<span class="c1"># Let's remove 2003 from our crime data.</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">></span> <span class="s1">'2003-12-31'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Make the date column the index of the data frame.</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DatetimeIndex</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">])</span> 

<span class="c1"># The crime data lists all individual crimes. </span>
<span class="c1"># We need to group it by month to compare it to the Google trend.</span>
<span class="n">crimes_month</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">())</span> 
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [6]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt"></div>
<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre><class 'pandas.core.frame.dataframe'>
DatetimeIndex: 162 entries, 2004-01-31 to 2017-06-30
Freq: M
Data columns (total 1 columns):
0    162 non-null int64
dtypes: int64(1)
memory usage: 2.5 KB
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now the <strong>crime_month</strong> data has a similar shape to the Google trend data. 162 entries and the same period.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Just renaming the column...</span>
<span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Total'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Taking a look at the data</span>
<span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea output_execute_result">
<div>

<tr style="text-align: right;">

<th>Total</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>DATE</th>
<th></th>
</tr>

<td>3767</td>

<td>3697</td>

<td>4042</td>
</tr>

</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The Total columns is the total number of crimes per month. To make it comparable to the Google trends, let's make a "crime index", in which the month that had the most number of crime will have a value of 100 and others will be relative to it.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Dividing the total number of crimes by the maximum value and round them</span>
<span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Total'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Total'</span><span class="p">]</span>
                               <span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">astype</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now let's join the two data frames.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">crime_trend</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">concat</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">crimes_month</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index'</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">googletrend</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">axis</span> <span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now let's smooth the trends by using a 24 months moving average.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [13]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Making a rolling average with a 24 window</span>
<span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">24</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index and Google Trend - 24 Months Moving Average'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">});</span>
</pre></div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now we can see the trends!</p>
<ul>
<li>Crime index and Search index decrease together until 2009.</li>
<li>From 2009 the Crime index keeps decreasing but the Search index stabilizes.</li>
<li>From 2013, both increase.</li>
</ul>
<p>We can visually identify a correlation, but let's check it for each period.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="Period-before-2009">Period before 2009<a class="anchor-link" href="#Period-before-2009">¶</a></h3><p>Let's check the correlation of the moving averages for the period before 2009.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Creating the moving average and assigning it to a data frame</span>
<span class="n">crime_before2009_rolling24</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="s1">'2009-01-01'</span><span class="p">]</span>
                              <span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">24</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [15]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Plot</span>
<span class="n">crime_before2009_rolling24</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index and Google Trend - Moving Average - Before 2009'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">});</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="Period-after-2013">Period after 2013<a class="anchor-link" href="#Period-after-2013">¶</a></h3><p>Let's do the same for the period after 2013</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [18]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Note: after 2013 regarding the moving average. </span>
<span class="c1"># Because it is a 24 months window, the data is after 2011</span>
<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling24</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">>=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-01-01'</span><span class="p">]</span>
                            <span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">24</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [19]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Plot</span>
<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling24</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index and Google Trend - Moving Average - After 2013'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">});</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<ul>
<li>0.99 Pearson correlation!</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="Using-a-6-months-moving-average">Using a 6 months moving average<a class="anchor-link" href="#Using-a-6-months-moving-average">¶</a></h3><p>A moving average with 24 months is great to see the general trend but it smooths out too much. Let's redo it with a 6 months window.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [22]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Now let's use a 6 months window</span>
<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crime_trend</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">>=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-01-01'</span><span class="p">]</span>
                            <span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">())</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [23]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Plot</span>
<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index and Google Trend - Moving Average - After 2013'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">});</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This is interesting. We can see that there is a <em>lag</em> between crime index and search index. When crime increases, it takes a while until searches increase. When crime index is reaching its local peak, the search start increasing.</p>
<p>Now let's redo this plot with a <em>lag</em> in the search index.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [24]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using .shift(-5) to lag the search index</span>
<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6_lagged</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">concat</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index'</span><span class="p">],</span>
                                             <span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Search Index'</span><span class="p">]</span>
                                             <span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shift</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">)],</span> <span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">crime_from2013_rolling6_lagged</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Crime Index'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Search Index (lagged)'</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [25]:</div>

entry.title: Interactive Tableau dashboard to explore Crime in Vancouver
entry.summary: A Tableau dashboard about crime in Vancouver's neighbourhoods.
entry.content:
This dashboard is meant to be used as a tool to visualize crime by neighbourhood. For an Exploratory Data Analysis, check here.




About the implementation

  • The animated map is playable only if you download the dashboard and open it in Tableau. The animation looks like this:

Example of the animated map

  • Converting UTM to Longitude and Latitude: the original data set includes UTM coordinates. In order to map it in Tableau, I converted it to Longitude and Latitude using a spreadsheet that can be found here: UTM Conversion

  • To draw the neighbourhood's boundaries, there is a data set that contains the shapes. The data set is called Local Area Boundary. A new feature of Tableau version 10.2 is that you can import this kind of file directly. Before that, you would need to use another software to convert the shape file to coordinates.

  • Tools used in this visualization: filters, context filters, highlighter, dashboard actions, URL action, animated map, map from shapes, sparkline, time-series, table calculation (moving average), dual axis, data source join, data source filter, data extract, tooltip, calculated field to get neighbourhood's initials and other calculated fields, dimension's hierarchies


Check more about crime in Vancouver.

entry.title: Tableau Certification
entry.content:
This week I got my Tableau 10 Qualified Associate Certification. This post is to share about this certification and give some tips.


About the Tableau Certification

There are two levels of certification:

  1. The Qualified Associate.
  2. The Certified Professional.

This post is about the Qualified Associate exam using Tableau Desktop 10 version.


Booking and Set up

You do everything online. From booking to the exam itself. Booking was easy with a lot of availability. Before the exam, you have some technical set up to do in order to be able to connect to the exam center. To do the exam, you have to connect via remote connection. You need a webcam and mic and your whole session is recorded.


The Exam

The exam duration is two hours. It has 36 questions, some are theoretical and some practical hands-on. To the practical questions, there are several data sets that you'll have to use. To pass it, you need a score of 75%. The cost of the exam is $250 USD and the results come right after you submit your answers. You also receive a report by email.


My experience

I finished in about one hour and a half and spend the rest of it reviewing my answers. I've got 100% correct. In my opinion, questions were straight forward and the exam was fair. It tests if you know how to use Tableau and how to answer some questions from the data. This exam does not test one's ability to tell a story from a data set. This would be the next level certification.


My preparation

I took one course at BCIT with Donnabel Santos, which I really recommend if you are in Vancouver. My practical experience is basically from that course and from some personal projects. Before the exam, I reviewed most of the Tableau training videos, which was important.


Some tips

There are free videos from Tableau training site which are really helpful. I recommend watching them. Even the basics videos can give you some tips. Tableau also offers two preparation courses but each costs $ 1,400 USD.

The Tableau preparation guide list all the functionality you should be prepared, which is almost everything. It also has sample questions that help to prepare.

Some things I had to do and I recommend you should know:

  • How to use the data interpreter.
  • How to make joins and the difference between outer and inner joins.
  • How to change a join connection manually.
  • How to create and use a set.
  • How to create a map.
  • How to measure distances on a map.
  • How to create calculated fields.
  • How to use table calculations.
  • How to calculate profit margins.
  • How to create dashboards actions.
  • How to use the Analytics functions.
  • I didn't have to use level of details calculation but it might be needed.
  • Read questions carefully and at least twice. Watch out for what the question asks for (for example, rank based on the sum or average).
  • Concepts about data connection and data extracting.
  • You can use the Internet to look out for answers. I only used the Tableau online documentation. It helps if you a familiar with the documentation beforehand. Know how to search for keywords. Some answers are straight forward to find in the documentation. Others aren't, so you have to figure it out.
  • You should be familiar with the sample superstore data set. Practice with it. Create calculated fields, sets, and explore the dimensions (category, segments, customers, etc).

Good luck!

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Introduction">Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#Introduction">¶</a></h1><hr />
<p>This is an Exploratory Data Analysis of crime in Vancouver.</p>
<p>This analysis was conducted using Python with Jupyter Notebook. This Notebook contains all the coding so that it can be replicated. It also contains coding comments, which some are basic comments that are meant to help others who might be learning Python.</p>
<h3 id="The-Data-set">The Data set<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Data-set">¶</a></h3><p>The data comes from the <a href="http://data.vancouver.ca/datacatalogue/crime-data.htm
" target="_blank">Vancouver Open Data Catalogue</a>.</p>
<p>It was extracted on 2017-07-18 and it contains 530,652 records from 2003-01-01 to 2017-07-13.</p>
<p>The original data set contains coordinates in UTM Zone 10. To convert the coordinates to Latitude and Longitude, I used a spreadsheet that can be found <a href="http://www.uwgb.edu/dutchs/UsefulData/HowUseExcel.HTM" target="_blank"> here</a>.</p>
<p>If you would like to use the same data, you can download it <a href="https://github.com/wosaku/datasets/raw/master/crimes_original_data.zip">here</a>.</p>
<h3 id="Data-Quality">Data Quality<a class="anchor-link" href="#Data-Quality">¶</a></h3><p>Please note that the data set does NOT include all crimes. For instance, the <a href="http://vancouver.ca/police/assets/pdf/annual-reports/vpd-annual-report-2016.pdf" target="_blank">Vancouver Police Department 2016 Annual Report</a> lists a total of 55,145 incidents for 2016. This data set has a total of 37,798 incidents for 2016, which corresponds to 69% of the official number. Also, this data set might change over time. For more details, see the Vancouver Open Data Catalogue description.</p>
<p><br /></p>
<h1 id="Importing-the-Data-Analysis-and-Visualization-packages">Importing the Data Analysis and Visualization packages<a class="anchor-link" href="#Importing-the-Data-Analysis-and-Visualization-packages">¶</a></h1><hr />
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Import data manipulation packages</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">np</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>

<span class="c1"># Import data visualization packages</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">seaborn</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">sns</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline

<span class="c1"># Ignore warning (Optional)</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">warnings</span>
<span class="n">warnings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">filterwarnings</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'ignore'</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Remove-unnecessary-columns">Remove unnecessary columns<a class="anchor-link" href="#Remove-unnecessary-columns">¶</a></h3><p>Column MINUTE can be deleted as we don't need to go to the minute level.
Columns regarding location (X, Y, Neighbourhood, Hundred block) won't be used in this analysis, but they will be used in the Tableau dashboard, so let's keep them for now.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Dropping column. Use axis = 1 to indicate columns and inplace = True to 'commit' the transaction</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">drop</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'MINUTE'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">axis</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Missing-Values">Missing Values<a class="anchor-link" href="#Missing-Values">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [6]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Let's take a look into our data to check for missing values and data types</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt"></div>
<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can see that we have 530,652 entries, but some columns (HOUR, HUNDRED_BLOCK and NEIGHBOURHOOD) have less, which means that there are missing values. Let's fill them.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># As HOUR is a float data type, I'm filling with a dummy value of '99'. For others, filling with 'N/A'</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'HOUR'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fillna</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">99</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'NEIGHBOURHOOD'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fillna</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'N/A'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'HUNDRED_BLOCK'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fillna</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'N/A'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Transforming-the-DATE-column">Transforming the DATE column<a class="anchor-link" href="#Transforming-the-DATE-column">¶</a></h3><p>The date is separated in different columns (YEAR, MONTH, DAY) , let's combine them into a single column and add it as a new column called 'DATE'</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Use pandas function to_datetime to convert it to a datetime data type</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_datetime</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s1">'year'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'YEAR'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'MONTH'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="s1">'day'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DAY'</span><span class="p">]})</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>It might be useful to have the day of the week...</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Let's use padas dt.dayofweek (Monday=0 to Sunday=6) and add it as a column called 'DAY_OF_WEEK'</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DAY_OF_WEEK'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dayofweek</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>When working with time series data, using the date as the index is helpful.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Change the index to the colum 'DATE'</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DatetimeIndex</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">])</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This dataset was extracted in 2017-07-18 and it contains partial data for this month. I'm excluding them to keep full months only.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Filtering the data to exclude month of July 2017</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o"><</span> <span class="s1">'2017-07-01'</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [12]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Let's check the data again</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Creating-Categories">Creating Categories<a class="anchor-link" href="#Creating-Categories">¶</a></h3><p>Let's see the type of crimes that we have in our data and categorize them.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [13]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using pandas value_counts function to aggregate types</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value_counts</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_index</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[13]:</div>
<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>Break and Enter Commercial                                 33787
Break and Enter Residential/Other                          60768
Homicide                                                     219
Mischief                                                   70253
Offence Against a Person                                   54035
Other Theft                                                51995
Theft from Vehicle                                        172265
Theft of Bicycle                                           25597
Theft of Vehicle                                           38359
Vehicle Collision or Pedestrian Struck (with Fatality)       254
Vehicle Collision or Pedestrian Struck (with Injury)       21871
Name: TYPE, dtype: int64</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>From the types above, I'm creating the following categories: Break and Enter, Theft, Vehicle Collision, Others</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [14]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a function to categorize types, using an 'if' statement.</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">category</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">if</span> <span class="s1">'Theft'</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="s1">'Theft'</span>
    <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="s1">'Break'</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="s1">'Break and Enter'</span>
    <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="s1">'Collision'</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="s1">'Vehicle Collision'</span>
    <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="s1">'Others'</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [15]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Apply the function and add it as CATEGORY column</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">category</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Although 'vehicle collision' is included in this data, I'll separate it apart because I believe it is a different kind of crime.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [16]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">vehicle_collision</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="s1">'Vehicle Collision'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'Vehicle Collision'</span><span class="p">]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now we have our data frame named <strong><em>crimes</em></strong> ready to analyze.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Exploratory-Data-Analysis">Exploratory Data Analysis<a class="anchor-link" href="#Exploratory-Data-Analysis">¶</a></h1><hr />
<h3 id="What's-the-distribution-of-crimes-per-day?">What's the distribution of crimes per day?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What's-the-distribution-of-crimes-per-day?">¶</a></h3><p>Let's start with a histogram of crimes per day.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [17]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using resample('D') to group it by day and size() to return the count</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Distribution of Crimes per day'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">distplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">bins</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">60</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
