<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li><p>We can see that the distribution looks like a <em>normal distribution</em> with a mean around <em>95 crimes per day</em>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>There is one outlier over 600. Let's find out which day it is.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="Outlier">Outlier<a class="anchor-link" href="#Outlier">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [18]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using idxmax() to find out the index of the max value</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">idxmax</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[18]:</div>
<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>Timestamp('2011-06-15 00:00:00', freq='D')</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>So the day was 2011-06-15.</p>
<p>Let's make a <em>time series graph</em> with crimes per day.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [19]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a Upper Control Limit (UCL) and a Lower Control Limit (LCL) without the outlier</span>
<span class="n">crimes_daily</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-06-15'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'MEAN'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-06-15'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'STD'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-06-15'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">std</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">UCL</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'MEAN'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="mi">3</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'STD'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">LCL</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'MEAN'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">3</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'STD'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Plot Total crimes per day, UCL, LCL, Moving-average</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'D'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Crimes per day'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">UCL</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ls</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'--'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">1.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'UCL'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">LCL</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ls</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'--'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">1.5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'LCL'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">crimes_daily</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'MEAN'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Average'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Total crimes per day'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Day'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Number of crimes'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">});</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can see some days over the Control Limits, indicating <em>signals</em>. Also, the period of 2003 to 2008 is above the average. Maybe a different Control Limit could be done for that period, but that's ok for now.</p>
<p>Let's focus on the day 2011-06-15 which is way above. Is that an error on the data?</p>
<p>Let's <em>drill down</em> and find out...</p>

<p>There are 647 occurrences, mostly mischief type, in the Central Business District, around the same hour but no exactly. They don't really seem to be duplicated entries.</p>
<h3 id="The-Stanley-Cup-Riot">The Stanley Cup Riot<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-Stanley-Cup-Riot">¶</a></h3><p>I moved to Canada in 2016 and I had no idea if something happened that day, so a Google search showed me it was the Stanley Cup's final game, Boston Bruins vs Vancouver Canucks. There were 155,000 people watching it in the downtown area. Before the game was over, as the Vancouver Canucks was about to loose it, a big riot started. It seems that it was ugly... If you want to know more about it, there is a <a href="http://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/law-crime-and-justice/criminal-justice/prosecution-service/reports-publications/stanley-cup-riot-prosecutions.pdf" target="_blank">21-pages report</a> by the BC Ministry of Justice.</p>
<p>So that day wasn't an error on the data and it showed me something that happened in Vancouver that I wasn't expecting at all. Interesting...</p>
<h3 id="Which-days-have-the-highest-and-lowest-average-number-crimes?">Which days have the highest and lowest average number crimes?<a class="anchor-link" href="#Which-days-have-the-highest-and-lowest-average-number-crimes?">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a pivot table with day and month; another that counts the number of years that each day had; and the average. </span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-06-15'</span><span class="p">)]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'YEAR'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'DAY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'MONTH'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table_year_count</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[(</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="s1">'2011-06-15'</span><span class="p">)]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'YEAR'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'DAY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'MONTH'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">unique</span><span class="p">()))</span>
<span class="n">crimes_average</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table_year_count</span>
<span class="n">crimes_average</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Jan'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Feb'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Mar'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Apr'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'May'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Jun'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Jul'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Aug'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Sep'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Oct'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Nov'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Dec'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Using seaborn heatmap</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">9</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Average Number of Crime per Day and Month'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_average</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">round</span><span class="p">(),</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'seismic'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'grey'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cbar</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">annot</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">".0f"</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Blue means good days. Red bad days. White average days.</p>
<ul>
<li>The calmest day of crime is Christmas Day, December 25 (30% below average). Criminals also celebrate with families...</li>
<li>The worst day is New Year's Day, January 1 (30% above average). And then after Christmas celebration, criminals take advantage of drunk people at parties?</li>
<li>The first day of the month is a busy day for all months.</li>
<li>Halloween (October 30,31 and November 1) are also dangerous days.</li>
<li>The second week of summer months are usually the most dangerous.</li>
<li>BC Day (August 7) long weekend have high averages.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="Is-crime-descreasing-or-increasing?">Is crime descreasing or increasing?<a class="anchor-link" href="#Is-crime-descreasing-or-increasing?">¶</a></h3><p>Now let's plot the number of crimes per month and a moving average:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [25]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using resample 'M' and rolling window 12</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Total per month'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'12-months Moving Average'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Crimes per month'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">''</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">})</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Average number of crimes per month decreased from 4,000 crimes per month to around 2,400 in the period of 2003 to 2011. That's really good!<ul>
<li>Vancouver hosted the 2010 Winter Olympics and the election for host city happened in 2003. So maybe the decrease of crimes is related to this event?</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>From 2011 to 2014, the moving average was around the same.</li>
<li>From 2014, the average has increased and 2016 reached similar leves of 2008.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="Is-this-trend-the-same-for-all-categories?">Is this trend the same for all categories?<a class="anchor-link" href="#Is-this-trend-the-same-for-all-categories?">¶</a></h3><p>Let's redo the plot but with categories.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [26]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Using pivot_table to groub by date and category, resample 'M' and rolling window 12</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'DATE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Moving Average of Crimes per month by Category'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">''</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">prop</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="s1">'size'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">})</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a pivot table with month and category. </span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'MONTH'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># To compare categories, I'm scaling each category by diving by the max value of each one</span>
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="c1"># Using a for loop to scale others</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">=</span>  <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>
                    
<span class="c1"># Using seaborn heatmap</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Month and Category heatmap'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'seismic'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'grey'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cbar</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Break and Enter has most incidents in January.</li>
<li>Theft and Others are more frequent during summer months. Maybe because people go out more and there is an increased number of tourists?</li>
<li>December is not a "good month" for Theft and Others. Or are thieves busy with Breaking and Entering people's home while they are travelling?</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="What-about-Day-of-the-Week?">What about Day of the Week?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What-about-Day-of-the-Week?">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [28]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a pivot table with day of the week and category. </span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'DAY_OF_WEEK'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># To compare categories, I'm scaling each category by diving by the max value of each one</span>
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="c1"># Using a for loop to scale row</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">()</span>
                    
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Mon'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Tue'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Wed'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Thu'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Fri'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Sat'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Sun'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Using seaborn heatmap</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Day of the Week and Category heatmap'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'seismic'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'grey'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cbar</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Break and Enter is more frequent on week days.</li>
<li>Theft and Others on weekends.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="What-hours-do-crimes-happen?">What hours do crimes happen?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What-hours-do-crimes-happen?">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [29]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a pivot table with hour and category. </span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'HOUR'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># To compare categories, I'm scaling each category by diving by the max value of each one</span>
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="c1"># Using a for loop to scale row</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">=</span>  <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>
                    
<span class="c1"># Using seaborn heatmap</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Hour and Category heatmap'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'seismic'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'grey'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cbar</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Most crimes happen between 17:00 and 20:00.</li>
<li>Break and Enter has some activity between 3 and 5 am.</li>
<li>Theft doesn't occur much in those hours between 3 and 5 as expected, because most people are sleeping.</li>
<li>Category Others doesn't have Hour in most of the entries (they are 'offset to protect privacy').</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="Do-crimes-happen-in-the-same-hour-for-each-day-of-the-week?">Do crimes happen in the same hour for each day of the week?<a class="anchor-link" href="#Do-crimes-happen-in-the-same-hour-for-each-day-of-the-week?">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [30]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Create a pivot table with hour and day of week. </span>
<span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'HOUR'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">!=</span> <span class="mi">99</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pivot_table</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'DAY_OF_WEEK'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'HOUR'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">aggfunc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="nb">len</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># To compare categories, I'm scaling each category by diving by the max value of each one</span>
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">())</span>

<span class="c1"># Using a for loop to scale each day</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">i</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">/</span> <span class="n">crimes_pivot_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Rename days of week</span>
<span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Mon'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Tue'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Wed'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Thu'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Fri'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Sat'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Sun'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1"># Using seaborn heatmap</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Hour and Day of the Week heatmap'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tick_params</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">labelsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">heatmap</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crimes_scaled</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cmap</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'seismic'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'grey'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">linewidths</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">cbar</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">);</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li><p>Here we can notice that week days have a different pattern than weekends.  It's like there is an additional <em>"crime working hours"</em> on weekends.</p>
</li>
<li><p>It looks like it makes sense that the City wanted to close Granville street clubs one hour earlier...</p>
<p>See: <a href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/granville-street-clubs-will-close-their-doors-1-hour-earlier-this-summer-1.4163233" target="_blank">Granville Street clubs will close their doors 1 hour earlier this summer.</a></p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id='Exploring-Category-"Theft"'>Exploring Category "Theft"<a class="anchor-link" href='#Exploring-Category-"Theft"'>¶</a></h3><p>We saw before that most crimes are in the category "Theft". Let's explore it better</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [31]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Let's check what types of theft we have and how many</span>
<span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="s1">'Theft'</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value_counts</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[31]:</div>
<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>Theft from Vehicle    172265
Other Theft            51995
Theft of Vehicle       38359
Theft of Bicycle       25597
Name: TYPE, dtype: int64</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><em>Theft from Vehicle</em> is the major type. Let's view each type over time.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [32]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Initiate the figure and define size</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="c1"># Using a for loop to plot each type of crime with a moving average</span>
<span class="n">i</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">221</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'CATEGORY'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="s1">'Theft'</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">unique</span><span class="p">():</span>    
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">i</span><span class="p">);</span>
    <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'Total per month'</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">crimes</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'TYPE'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">resample</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'M'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rolling</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">window</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">mean</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">label</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'12-months Moving Average'</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">crime_type</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">14</span><span class="p">)</span>

kmrCAZwkSZIk1YQDOEmSJEmqif8BCTa0hnZmHjcAAAAASUVORK5CYII=
" />
</div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>First, let me start with "Theft of Vehicle:<ul>
<li>It had a major decrease, from an average of around 520 crimes per month in 2003 to around 100 in 2012. That's impressive!</li>
<li>Although the average has been increasing in the past years, it's way below 2003.</li>
<li>In 2002, the <a href="http://www.baitcar.com/about-impact-bait-car-program" target="_blank">"Bait Car"</a> program was launched and in 2003 the IMPACT group was formed in response to this peak in theft. It looks like they've been doing a great job!</li>
<li>Side note: I wonder if this decrease of around 80% in the number of theft had any impact on insurance policies prices...</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Second, about "Other Theft":<ul>
<li>On the opposite trend, other theft has been increasing, from around 200 to almost 500 crimes per month.</li>
<li>Is it because stealing a car became too risky, but thieves still need to "make a living"?</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>About "Theft from Vehicle":<ul>
<li>It is the most frequent type.</li>
<li>It decreased along with "Theft of Vehicle" until 2012, but then it increased significantly.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Finally, about "Theft of Bicycle":<ul>
<li>We can see a clear trend within the year. It has peaks during summer months, which is expected.</li>
<li>The average has also been increasing.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="That's-it-for-this-section!">That's it for this section!<a class="anchor-link" href="#That's-it-for-this-section!">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>

<h2 id="Introduction">Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#Introduction">¶</a></h2><hr />
<p>This post provides a brief overview of data profiling tools and a python custom function to run a <em>mask analysis</em>.</p>
<p><br /><br /></p>
<h2 id="Data-Profiling">Data Profiling<a class="anchor-link" href="#Data-Profiling">¶</a></h2><hr />
<p>The idea of Data Profiling is to use <em>descriptive statistics</em> to make an informative summary of the data. It's an interesting process and it's very useful in <em>data quality projects</em> and <em>data warehouse</em>.</p>
<p>There are several options of software for <em>Data Quality</em>. In the course 'Data Quality Improvement' at BCIT, we used the <a href="https://www.ataccama.com/products/data-discovery-and-profiling/dqa" target="_blank">Ataccama DQ Analyzer</a>. It's a free desktop software.</p>
<p>In this post, I'm using the data set <a href="http://data.vancouver.ca/datacatalogue/businessLicence.htm" target="_blank">Business Licence</a> (edited version) from the Vancouver Open Data Catalogue as an example.</p>
<p><br />
<strong>Screenshot from Ataccama DQ Analyzer</strong>
<img src="images/data-quality-screenshot.png" />
<br /></p>
<p>In the screenshot, we can see the basic statistics, frequency and mask analysis.</p>
<p>The advantage of using a Data Quality software is that once you import the data, it will make the profile for all columns. It is easy to navigate and if you are connected to a database, you can drill down by simply double-clicking a field.</p>
<p>But if you just want to make a quick profile, you are using python and don't want to import the data into another software, there are some pandas function that can do it. Additionally, there is a nice package called pandas-profiling. However, it does not have a mask analyzer, so I'm providing an additional custom function.</p>
<p><br /><br /></p>
<h2 id="Data-Profiling-with-Pandas">Data Profiling with Pandas<a class="anchor-link" href="#Data-Profiling-with-Pandas">¶</a></h2><hr />
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This package gives some nice warning and for numerical fields, it also gives a histogram.</p>
<p>It doesn't have a Mask Analysis. So I wrote one myself.</p>
<p><br /><br /></p>
<h2 id="Mask-Analysis-custom-function">Mask Analysis custom function<a class="anchor-link" href="#Mask-Analysis-custom-function">¶</a></h2><hr />
<p>The mask analysis or string pattern is useful for fields like city, postal code, phone, etc. It shows us how the fields have been populated and we can infer some data quality issues.</p>
<p>Rules:</p>
<ul>
<li>lower case letter returns 'l'</li>
<li>Capital case letter returns 'L'</li>
<li>Number returns 'D'</li>
<li>Space returns 's'</li>
<li>Special character returns itself</li>
<li>Missing value returns '-null-'</li>
</ul>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
<li>'Van' returns 'Lll'</li>
<li>'VAN' returns 'LLL'</li>
<li>'Van BC' returns 'LllsLL'</li>
<li>'+1 123-1234-5555 returns '+DsDDD-DDDD-DDDD'</li>
<li>The standard for the Canadian Postal Code should be 'LDLsDLD'</li>
</ul>
<p>Let's run the function and see an example:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [9]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">mask_profile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">series</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">'''</span>
<span class="sd">    Make a mask profile of a field by converting the ascii value of the character as below.</span>
<span class="sd">    a to z --> returns "l" for letter</span>
<span class="sd">    A to Z --> returns "L" for Letter</span>
<span class="sd">    0 to 9 --> returns "D" for Digit</span>
<span class="sd">    'space' --> returns "s" for space</span>
<span class="sd">    Special characters --> keep original</span>
<span class="sd">    Requirement: pandas</span>
<span class="sd">    Input: pandas Series</span>
<span class="sd">    '''</span>    
    <span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">getMask</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">field</span><span class="p">):</span>
        <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">''</span>
        <span class="k">if</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">field</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="s1">'nan'</span><span class="p">:</span>
            <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'-null-'</span>
        <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>    
            <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">character</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">field</span><span class="p">):</span>
                <span class="k">if</span> <span class="mi">65</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">character</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="mi">90</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="c1"># ascii 65 to 90 are Capital letters</span>
                    <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'L'</span>                
                <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="mi">97</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">character</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="mi">122</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="c1">#ascii 97 to 122 are lower case letters</span>
                    <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'l'</span>
                <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="mi">48</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">character</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o"><=</span> <span class="mi">57</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="c1">#ascii 48 to 57 are digits</span>
                    <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'D'</span>
                <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">character</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="mi">32</span><span class="p">:</span>
                    <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'s'</span>
                <span class="k">else</span><span class="p">:</span>
                    <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mask</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">character</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">mask</span>
    <span class="n">value</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">series</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">getMask</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value_counts</span><span class="p">()</span>
    <span class="n">percentage</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">round</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">series</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">apply</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">getMask</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value_counts</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">normalize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">value</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">result</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'%'</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">percentage</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">result</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Count'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'%'</span><span class="p">]</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">result</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To use this function:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Use mask_profile(pass a pandas series)</span>
<span class="c1"># I'm using head(10) to show only the top 10 results</span>
<span class="n">mask_profile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'PostalCode'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
